",,"----------------------------------------------------------------------------
This one of Switchfoot's mellow songs and it's one of my favorites
from the album Learning To Breathe. The guitar uses a lot of
individual note picking and simple chords. Its a simple song and
here's how I play it. If you like it, go ahead and rate it!
INTRO: Basically, you just make a G chord and hit these individual
notes. You play this 4x through and there is a little bit of
variation sometimes with the individual notes but this is most of it.
At the end of the 2nd time you play the extra fill that goes
in between the two divisions of the intro. Then repeat this again.
This is the fill that is played after the 1st time
through (0:15) and then again just before the verse.
G    D     D  G             G    D     D  G
PRECHORUS: ""Where will I find you?"" For the 1st chord here, make
sure you do an upstroke on the 1st chord or it will sound wrong!
The rest of the chords can just be played with normal downstrokes.
CHORUS: This is played 2 times but there are some extra
individual notes added in some places. These are the notes
you use though and you can mess around with them if you want.
VERSE 2: Once again there is a lot of variation to the
individualnotes but these are the notes you use.
BRIDGE: ""Where was I when the world was made""
Use up and down strokes and play till Outro.
OUTRO: Same as Intro with variations in the individual notes.
This is the fill that is in the place of the one used

Excellent job here.
Those interested in playing this on a mandolin should be able to figure this out from the videos on YouTube. But I'll help out anyway.

Standard tuning, though Jon plays with the tone on his (very nice) acoustic-electric mando. GDAE
The intro is the low end of a G chop chord, played as 75XX. Look close and you can see Jon throw in 79XX, but you should be fine without it.
Some versions on YouTube have Jon playing on the verses, some don't, but the chords are implied, and here they are correct. Though on a mandolin, just play them as 0003(Em), 0230(C), 0023(G) and 2002(D).
Same chord shapes for the chorus. You make the Em stand out a little more as 4003.

The bridge is kind of weird... As far as I can tell, for the first two lines, Jon plays two chords. The first is 3053(Am?), with a slide down to 5075(Bm?). But the rest of the bridge is the same chords as above, with D replacing Dsus2.

So yeah, great job, great song. Hope this helps.

from ""'C' is for (Please Insert Sophomoric Genitalia Reference Here""
Great song - makes me wish I could play violin :D
Listen to the song, tap your foot, and you'll get the rhythm.
Nature, nurture, heaven and home                           The
Sum of all and by them driven                             To
Conquer every mountain shown                         But I’ve
Braved the forest, braved the stone,
Braved the icy wind and fire
Braved and beat them on my own
But I’m helpless by the river.
The intro is the same picking pattern as the verses, except that it starts mid-bar, on
C#. So basically there’s this little pattern and then you start playing the verse.
That’s the main acoustic picking part for the whole song. As the violin comes in with
hands of the many must join as one, It'll take a lot more than words and guns...' The
(or maybe its a mandolin?) starts strumming F# with a similar pattern, and other
come and go as Maynard & co. see fit.
Once you get the rhythm and get in the habit of coming in strong on the first beat of
bar this song is lots of fun to sing with.

",,"Artist: Puscifer
Album: C is for (Please Insert Sophomoric Genitalia Reference HERE)
This is the correct way to play the song. The other versions are basically correct
however they are a half step down from how the song should be played. This is a half
from the other tabs, and seems to be in the correct key. I mean c'mon, you really think
Maynard is going to sing in B flat...more like A or D like every Tool song ever written.
Also I'm using the open G string instead of the 5th fret on the D string because it
sounds like the guitar in the song actually is hitting the open G.If you want you can play
the G note on the D string 5th fret, you have to reach a little bit and it looks way
cooler playing it, however it doesn't quite have the right sound to it.

Notes: yes, this song was originally done by the Kings of Leon. But Tyrone did his
own version of this, and it’s currently one of my favorites.
It’s possible to play this without a capo of course, but 1. it’s how he does it
live and 2. it’s easier this way. Note: start with your middle and ring fingers on
the third frets for the first chord.
(At “You know…that I could use somebody”, then “it’s gonna make you notice”)
Start strumming down at “Someone like me”, emphasis on the 1,4, and 7th chords.
Bridge (“I’m ready...”, strumming up + down now. Play each chord 8x, repeat line 2x)
End Sequence (this just goes back and forth between the original two lines, strum
or pick out as you feel)
Outro (the very last “I’m been roaming…”; it’s picked)
Tabbed by: Czerald G. Guevarra - biboy_0916@yahoo.com
